prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Band 8 continuum + CO(14-13) for J0903
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: 2x2 mosaic centred at the Herschel coordinates. 3 spws in continuum one in FDM mode to target the CO(14-13) line.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Line widths in extragalactic distant objects are at least 300km/s large. Correlator is set at a channel width of ~1MHz, which with an averaging of a factor of 16 will become ~8MHz, drastically reducing the data rate and increasing the sensitivity. Our computed sensitivity is over 100km/s, which makes a S/N of 1.5 for the faintest source (5mJy), increasing up to 5 for the brightest sources.

Targets are submm galaxies detected by Herschel and APEX/LABOCA, which are expected to be resolved at 0.3-0.4" (i.e. Simpson et al., 2014). Angular resolution is set to 0.4 arcsec, likely to resolve all the requested sources. In this band to recover angular scales as large as 10" ACA is needed. The requirement comes from the unknown source extension, being this source detected by Herschel and APEX whose highest spatial resolution is 18".

Goal of this proposal is imaging and identifying Herschel/LABOCA detected sources and determine the spectroscopic redshift. Sensitivity is large enough for continuum detection, having the targets a detected flux at 600 GHz of 30-100mJy and at 340GHz of 10-70mJy. CO line is primarily used to infer the spectroscopic redshift, the sensitivity is based on its extimated integrated flux, on a width of 300km/s, which is the minimum width detected in high redshift sources. Peak line flux is only rough estimated on the basis of the ratio between continuum-dust/CO-line flux detected in submm galaxies.
Band 8 is a non-standard mode in cycle 3. Paola Andreani is ready to invest her time to reduce the data and provide feedback to the observatory on their quality.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The combination of APEX/LABOCA, and near-IR (SPITZER/VIKING) photometry of far infrared galaxies colour-selected from blind Herschel surveys strongly hints at the presence of overdensities of sources at redshift ~3, in fields containing lensed galaxies. These sources share the same physical properties of the lensed galaxies and are very likely physically associated with them, suggesting the hypothesis of forming galaxy clusters. ALMA observations in Band 8 and 6 (i.e. both sides of the LABOCA filter) and in Band 3 and 4 targeting 22 of the z~3 candidates will unveil the nature of these sources, complement the photometry and likely detecting CO ((3-2), (5-4), (8-7), (14-13)) , HCN, HCO+ and CS lines. These lines will be used not only to determine the spectroscopic redshift but more fundamentally to study the physical environment of these sources, probing the thermal and dynamical states of their large molecular gas reservoirs. The ALMA high spatial resolution will unveil clumpiness within the Herschel sources and substructures that eventually may interact before the cluster virialisation is reached at later stages, confirming the nature of these fields as hosts of a protocluster.
